From <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">stylus</SPAN>, an instrument for writing; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#note74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on <I>Jul.</I> lxxxii.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note5" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">5</A>
The pun consists in likening him to the Sicilian Daphnis, the "ideal shepherd," whom Pan taught to play the shepherd's pipe. If we read <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἄγασμα</SPAN>, the meaning is "the prodigy (or '<SPAN CLASS="whole">wonder-child</SPAN>') of Pan." The early commentators saw a reference to Pan's love for the flocks and


<A ID="p401x"></A>shepherds (<I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ec02.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Vergil\'s <I>Eclogues</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Pan primum</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Verg. <I>Buc.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.33</A>) and an implication that Lutatius was <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">rusticus</SPAN> or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pecus</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note6" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">6</A>
The text is certainly corrupt and the meaning is uncertain; see Ihm, <I>Rh. Mus.</I> 61, p550.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
