onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Epist.</I> 2.1.70</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note20" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref20
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A>
Varro Murena. Macrobius,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Macrobius/Saturnalia/2*.html#6
	"TARGET="Macrobius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Sat.</I> 2.6</A>, tells the same story of Galba, father of the emperor (<I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Galba*.html#3.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Galba</I>, iii</A>), but gives the reply of Orbilius as: "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">in sole gibbos soleo fricare</SPAN>," "I rub humps in the sun." Neither remark seems to have any point


<A ID="p411x"></A>except the allusion to Murena's deformity, unless Suetonius's version means "I put them into the background," or "consign them to obscurity." The commentators confine themselves to quoting Macrobius.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
The text is corrupt and no satisfactory emendation has as yet been proposed; see Ihm, <I>Rh. Mus.</I> 61, p551. Vahlen, <I>Index Lectionum</I>, Berlin, 1877, suggested <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">theoremata</SPAN>, which would give the meaning "and afterwards taught his (Gnipho's) theories."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>
A Greek word, equivalent to <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Silva</SPAN>, meaning literally "timber" for building, and used metaphorically of material


<A ID="p413x"></A>in a rough form; here of material for oratory. <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Silva</SPAN> is also applied technically to hasty and more or less extempore productions; <I>cf.</I> <!-- Loeb italicizes "Quint." --><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Quintilian/Institutio_Oratoria/10B*.html#3.17
	"TARGET="Quintilian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Quint. 10.3.17</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">diversum est huic eorum vitium, qui primo decurrere per materiam stilo quam velocissimo volunt et sequentes calorem atque impetum ex tempore scribunt; hanc silvam vocant.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
That is, his own, without borrowing or imitation.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
Dictynna is a name of Diana as goddess of the chase, from <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">δίκτυον</SPAN>, "<SPAN CLASS="whole">hunting-net</SPAN>."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Unum expedire nomen</SPAN>, "make shift to find one name," as surety for his debts.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
That is, "what a fate for a man with such a mind and heart." <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Cor</SPAN> here, as often, = "intelligence," and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">iecur</SPAN> may have the same meaning, although it is commonly spoken of as the seat of the emotions, especially anger and the like.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note27" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref27
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">calatores</SPAN>, literally "summoners," were attendants on the augurs and other religious officials.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Catasta</SPAN> was the scaffolding or platform on which slaves were exposed to view at public sales.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/fam9.shtml#10
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Ad Fam.</I> 9.10</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
The critical mark used to indicate spurious or interpolated lines; that is, Vidius denies the debt.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/att12.shtml#26
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Ad Att.</I> 12.26</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Tiberius*.html#note26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on <I>Tib.</I> xv.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#66
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Aug.</I> lxvi.1‑2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
Q. Lutatius Catulus; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#3.6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. iii
	</A>
and Index.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
A <SPAN CLASS="whole">semi-circular</SPAN> place for sitting; applied also by Vitruvius,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Vitruvius/9*.html#8.1
	"TARGET="Vitruvius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
9.9.1</A>,<!-- sic Loeb; in my edition, 9.8.1 --> to a kind of sundial.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
The <I>Fasti Praenestini</I>, of which fragments have come down to us.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
A <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pergula</SPAN> was an upper floor or balcony on the front of a house; such balconies were used as shops, studios, schools, and the like; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#94.12
	"TARGET="Suetonius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Aug.</I> xciv.12</A>.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For full details, see the article
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Pergula.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pergula
	</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#62.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Aug.</I> lxii.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#29.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Aug.</I> xxix.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Tiberius*.html#note13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on <I>Tib.</I> vii.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#29.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Aug.</I> xxix.4</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">fabulae togatae</SPAN> presented scenes from Roman life, in


<A ID="p427x"></A>contrast with the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">fabulae palliatae</SPAN>, or comedies adapted from the Greek.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Domitian*.html#note58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">trabea</SPAN>, Dom. xiv.3</A>. In the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">trabeatae</SPAN> the characters were knights or other wearers of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">trabea</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
To dodge a blow delivered with the right hand; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ae05.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 5<BR>of Vergil\'s <I>Aeneid</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'abduxere</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Verg. <I>Aen.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.428</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">abduxere retro longe capita ardua ab ictu</SPAN>; part of the instruction to a boxer.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Os</SPAN> is of course used in a double sense, figuratively as above, and literally, of a pugilist's battered visage.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
As <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">paedagogus</SPAN>, <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Nero*.html#36.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Nero</I>, xxvi.2</A>, etc.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ec03.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Vergil\'s <I>Eclogues</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'ecce Palaemon</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
3.50 ff.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
Naturally, on literary and grammatical topics.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#note22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on <I>Hyle</I>, chap. x</A>.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Orbilius.name" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref:Orbilius.name
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
This passage is cited as the only one in ancient literature giving Orbilius' first name; yet "Lucius" is a modern addition (see
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#note21
	"TARGET="Suetonius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
the critical note to the Latin text</A>): I have not read Roth's reasons. The rest of the name can be translated as "orphan, ward" (see the article
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Impubes.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Impubes
	</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>): if his parents died when he was young, as strongly suggested by our text, he was both.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Orbilius_statue" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref:Orbilius_statue
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
The statue is not known to be extant; although several Roman statues are shown in Benevento as being that of Orbilius, none matches Suetonius' description. I love Italy dearly, but connecting things and places with the more famous persons and events of Antiquity is something of a national sport: visitors beware.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:peculium" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref:peculium
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
For details on the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">peculium</SPAN> and the procedure — which this passage does not quite seem to fit — see the article
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Servus.html#peculium
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,SmithSub1,WIDTH,SmithSubWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Servus
	</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify" ID="note:infamiam_oris">
	<A CLASS="note" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref:infamiam_oris1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">d1</A>
	<A CLASS="note" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/de_Grammaticis*.html#ref:infamiam_oris2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">d2</A>
The translator, in editing out the filthiness of the joke, has sacrificed the joke itself. A dirty story is a dirty story, and there's nothing much you can do about it.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
The Latin words <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">usque ad infamiam oris</SPAN>, here rendered by "to the pitch of shameful indecency", actually mean "to the degradation of his mouth". Roman men, who viewed as shameful anything other than penetration (<A HREF="
https://www.curculio.org/Juvenal/s09.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Juvenal\'s 9th Satire'+Lat2+LatSearch+'quid tibi</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Juv. <SPAN CLASS="small">IX</SPAN>.3‑5</A>, the famous passage on mirrors in
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/sen/sen.qn1.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Seneca\'s Natural Questions'+Lat2+LatSearch+'scelera</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Sen. <I>Quaest. Nat.</I> 1.16.4‑7</A>,
	<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lspost01/Martialis/mar_ep07.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 7<BR>of the Epigrams of Martial'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Non fellat</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Mart. <SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN>.67.13‑17</A>, and, best known,
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/catullus.shtml#16
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Catullus <SPAN CLASS="small">XVI</SPAN></A>), would almost certainly have read this as referring to cunnilingus — which makes it quite clear why, in an age far less given than ours to mouthwashes and toothpaste (although they did have them, see for example the article
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Dentifricium.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Dentifricium
	</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>), that guy in the crowd wanted to get away from Palaemon, and in a hurry, too. In turn, in his <I>bon mot</I>, the verb rendered by our translator "to mouth" is a specific word, often with sexual connotations, meaning "to lick away": see Suetonius himself, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ligurire</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Tiberius*.html#45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Tib.</I> 45</A>.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Here, then, is my own suggestion towards a better translation: "Hey man, every time you see someone coming at you in a hurry, do you want to lick 'em clean?"
	</P>



